Raw dev notes -- Title idea: "Wrestling with Data: OCR, Monitors, and the Never-Ending Quest for Clean Info"

Okay, so this past week or so has been a deep dive into the guts of the RAG knowledge base pipeline. The whole point of this project is to build a robust system that can ingest a ton of diverse content – articles, Q&As, transcripts, you name it – and make it searchable and usable for our RAG models. Basically, turning a mountain of unstructured data into a smart, queryable resource. It's all about getting good, clean data into the system so the AI can actually do its job well.

What's been happening lately? A few big things. First, I finally got around to tackling Hebrew OCR. This was a pretty big step because a lot of our source material is in Hebrew, and often it's scanned documents or images. I put together a notebook for it, which feels like a solid foundation, and made sure to link up the backup info for the processed files. It's one thing to process, another to make sure you don't lose the output!

Then, the big one: I built out a new content monitor for a specific source. This thing is designed to automatically download new content and push it through our conversion pipeline. It sounds simple, but getting it right was a bit of a beast. I spent a good chunk of time fixing it up. Initially, it was a bit naive, but I refined the URL matching to be manifest-based, which is way more robust. Also, had to make sure it wasn't downloading duplicates – nothing worse than redundant data clogging up the system – so canonical URL checks were crucial. And the conversion itself needed tweaking; turns out Q&A content needs a different touch than regular articles, so `convert_all.py` got some love to handle both properly. Oh, and a small but annoying fix: parsing dates for answers. Sometimes there's an author prefix that messes things up, so I added logic to strip that out and fall back to the published date if needed. Data cleaning, man, it's always the little things that bite you. I also noted down a big chunk of ~2,000 online lesson transcripts waiting in the wings, but that's currently blocked on someone else.

The hardest part, honestly, was getting that content monitor to be truly reliable. It's one thing to write a script that downloads *some* stuff, another to build something that consistently and correctly ingests *all* new content without breaking or duplicating. The manifest-based URL matching was a bit of a head-scratcher to get right, and ensuring the `convert_all.py` script correctly identified and processed different content types (Q&A vs. articles) took some trial and error. Each "fix monitor" commit represents a small battle won against the chaos of real-world data. And the Hebrew OCR, while the notebook is there, I know the real challenge will be scaling it and ensuring accuracy across various document qualities. It's a whole new domain for me, diving into the nuances of language-specific OCR. Also, seeing that "blocked on Oren" for those ~2,000 lesson transcripts is a reminder that sometimes, the biggest blockers aren't technical, but human or logistical.

It's been a mix of satisfaction and mild frustration. There's a real sense of accomplishment when you see the monitor pull in new content flawlessly, or when the OCR actually spits out readable Hebrew. But then there's the grind of debugging why a date isn't parsing correctly, or why a URL is being missed. It really hammers home the importance of robust, fault-tolerant data pipelines. You can have the fanciest RAG model in the world, but if the data going in is garbage, the output will be too. This whole process is teaching me a lot about the "dirty work" of AI – the data engineering side that often gets overlooked but is absolutely critical. It's a reminder that building reliable systems means anticipating every possible way things can go wrong and putting safeguards in place. It feels like I'm leveling up my data wrangling skills, which is a good feeling.

Next up: Get those ~2,000 online lesson transcripts processed once they're unblocked.
